3 Xenophon says that a eonvention was made between Cyrus and the Assyrians, that there should be peace with the cultivacor, war with the soldiers. So Timotheus let the most fertile part of the land to hus- bandmen, as Polyaenus relates, and even, as Aristotle adds, sold the produce to the enemy, to raise money to pay his soldiers; and so Viriatus did in Spain. And the same was done in the Belgicu- Germanic war of which we have spoken, with great reason, and great advantage, to the admiration of foreigners.

4 These practices are proposed for imitation by the Canens, the teachers of humanity, to all Christians, as owing and professing a humanity greater than other men. And therefore these Canons direct, not only that cultivators should be out of danger of war, but animals sor the plough, and the seed for sowing.
